,Not Recommended,434420,21214390,"Posted: 14 February, 2016",all,Erbkaiser,"This game is too cheaply made to really be worth your time. The story is cookie fodder -- early -- Final Fantasy fare, the chosen hero has to save the world yadda yadda yadda.The only unique feature which tries to set it apart from other RPGMaker games is the cheesecake portraits of female characters, which heavily feature in the store front screenshots.The main problem is easily seen in all the random battles: there is absolutely no art consistency in this game. Backgrounds are pixel paintings, player characters are minute chibi sprites and as for the enemies, they are without exception several times larger than the player sprites and of various differing art styles, ranging from generic slime to highly detailed soldier. Battles use RPGMaker default rules and there isn't even a selection cursor showing just which of the many enemies on screen is 'Soldiers A' and which is 'Soldiers D' -- note the plural.The game text has multiple grammar and spelling errors, and even complete novice errors such as referring to a DESCENDANT of someone as ANCESTOR.Other problems include the complete lack of indicators on sprites that are affected by status impairments such as poisoned, while with player characters there is some indicator in the battle screens, there is no such info for enemies. Combine with the lack of identification of individual enemies and you have to remember which enemy has which status...There is also no health bar for enemies, or even any indication that they may be close to death. Fortunately (?) they are all very easy. Without grinding, I only died once during the entire game, and that was a scripted loss. Even the optional bosses are extremely easy to beat.On top of all that, the game ends on a clfifhanger with a 'to be continued'.All in all, if this were a free RPGMaker game I'd be supportive of it as the game creator does have a good idea of what makes a decent oldschool RPG game, but for a commercial release that is sold for money, I expect more. So I just can't honestly recommend it."
76561198042646749,Not Recommended,434420,34535815,Posted: 27 August,all,kris.aalst,"The Chosen RPGis a generic old-school role-playing game made with RPG Maker. Gameplay-wise, it ticks all the boxes but there's nothing to this game that'll blow you away. Add to that a very clichéd story and a strange choice of avatars (the scantily-clad girls), and we're left with nothing but a slightly above-average RPG Maker game.'Nudity' tagYou've noticed the 'nudity' tag and maybe also the screenshots showing scantily-clad girls, so let's talk about the nudity for a moment: there is none. There's just the portraits of the three girls you'll recruit as party members, which shows them in underwear. But beyond that, there's no nudity or even any innuendo in this game. Not one bit.The decision to portray the three girls in their underwearandto show those portraits as three of the six screenshots on the Steam Store page is most likely the worst decision I've ever seen in game development. It's a very, very bad call because people add the 'nudity' label to the game, even though that's inaccurate, with the following consequences:- people who're looking for nudity won't find it in this game so they won't be happy;- people who're not looking for nudity may stay away from the game after glancing at it and seeing the screenshots and/or the 'nudity' label;- because of the 'nudity' label, Steam always displays a warningevery timeyou openanypage related to the game (store page, guides, discussions, achievements page, …), which gets very annoying.StoryThe story is one big cliché: an adolescent has a dream about his missing father and is dubbed the 'chosen one' to fulfil a prophecy that tells him to gather some sacred artifacts in order to defeat an evil warrior who's at the service of an even more evil warrior. The game tries to shake things up by adding a twist to the story at the end, but the player most likely saw it coming a mile away, especially people who've seen Star Wars.To make matters worse, the paper-thin story ends with 'To be continued…' after defeating the final boss. So if you want to see the conclusion to the story, you'll need to buyChosen 2. Lame.The writing is okay in that we usually get to read a lot worse English in these RPG Maker games, but nevertheless the wording is sometimes strange e.g. 'Potion was found' and 'Wanna beer?'.GameplayThe gameplay is typical RPG Maker. You walk around towns, enter houses and stores, leave the town and explore the surroundings where random combat may be initiated at any time. You control a party, in this case a group of four, and equip them with increasingly better gear. By defeating opponents in tactical turn-based combat, the party members gain levels, increasing their stats (hit points, magic points, attack and defense) and allowing them to learn new skills and spells.The level design is decent. You'll find yourself in towns, forests, deserts, castles and dungeons - classic stuff, really. The game world seems open at first, but you'll soon learn that you always need to complete the next part of the main quest at location A to be able to enter location B, where the next part of the main quest will take place. So the game is actually very linear.The combat is made interesting by adding a mix of skills and spells. Skills use TP that are gained during combat. Spells use classic MP. It takes a few levels before the party gains access to interesting skills and spells, making the first part of the game very repetitive combat-wise. Also, you'll soon find out which are the most useful skills and spells, and likewise discover that most of the other skills and spells are actually completely useless.Overall,The Chosen RPGis a bit too easy, so I'm sure a lot of people would have preferred to see an option to set the game to a higher difficulty mode. The good thing about the low difficulty is thatThe Chosen RPGrequires little or no level grinding, unlike a lot of other RPG Maker games.During combat you sometimes get status effects that persist after the combat has ended, but there's no way to check what these status effects are exactly.Your party gains levels but the game doesn't mention how much stats they gain. You do get a notice if they gain a skill or spell, though, which is the most useful information.Graphics and soundThe graphics are classic RPG Maker graphics. But the problem withThe Chosen RPGis that Windowed Mode is too small, whereas Full Screen Mode has wide black bars to the left and right of the screen, and it renders the graphics way too blurry, as graphics get blown up too much to fill the screen. So an option for an in-between size would have been very welcome.One further gripe is that your party members are tiny. During combat, they're literally five times smaller than any human opponent, even though your party does not consist of toddlers or dwarves. It just looks ridiculous.The Chosen RPG's music is fine except for the annoying 1990s dance music in the starting town. To make matters worse, a bit later on, when that town is under attack, the music changes to a groovy jazz tune. Both are completely out of place. But okay, the rest of the music is fine and combat music is even reminiscent of classic old-school JRPGs, so it's just unfortunate that the problem with the music lies in the very first area of the game.On Steam's extra featuresThe Chosen RPGhas 5 Steam Trading Cards. You'll get 3 while running the game.Five of the 8 Steam Achievements are story-related and unmissable. The remaining 3 are granted for optional goals and therefore missable."
