76561197993118789,Not Recommended,434420,34180451,Posted: 11 August,all,nerloch,"Yet another RPG Maker game we have on Steam, but is this the one that will redeem all the wannabe-SNES JRPG copycats we’ve been swarmed by lately?The Chosen is…+ Experimental with somewhat inherently busted skill system, but in the good way: every RPG Maker games suffers from it in some way, since the easily exploitative and spammy skill system offers the player to become too imbalanced after only a few gained levels. The Chosen remedies this by including separate skill bar that keep filling as the combat goes on, especially when the player takes a massive damage. You can use skills that cost next to nothing on the skill bar to produce basic but sufficiently powerful combat abilities, or you can wait for the higher tier skills that cost more for battle changers.+ Playful with skills: basic ones are satisfying to use and powerful. Our main hero has a useful power attack that deals a double damage, while one of his companions has the Tackle that has a chance to prevent the enemies’ next attack, and is one of the most useful skills in the game.- Very short: you can finish this game in 4-6 hours easily, and the replayability is next to zero due to serious lack of content.- Unambitious, way too much generic: The Chosen is a painfully “by the numbers” JRPG game, there are literary no interesting quests except “fetch me this” and “get that bloke!” generic quests. Level design is poor and simplistic, battles are boring and grindy, there are no interesting characters, whether they are main heroes, few and rare NPCs that you meet, not to mention the main villain.- A bit too much asset-flipping: too much of generic assets, not enough of original artwork. RPG Maker is a powerful JRPG maker that comes with a sizeable library of audio and visual assets, but that does not mean you should use them in the product you’re selling, because this feels cheap, lazy and effortless. Except the skimpy design of the main heroes and a handful of NPCs, along with one or two enemies, everything else is an asset flip. Putting as much effort in your product as you can with your artwork always pays off since people who play notice this, and respect the developers who’ve put a proper effort in making as best game they can. So after designing story and screenplay, this should be you next priority.- Narratively poor: Since the game mechanics in RPG Maker games are inherently simplistic and anarchic by the nature of the game engine they’re based on, story should be your number one priority. An interesting and involving story can and will remedy the many flaws a game can have with most of the players. Sadly, the story in The Chosen is childish, full of plot holes and unsatisfying. Characters that populate this world have even worse treatment since they are walking and spewing trope generators, utterly boring and one-dimensional, without proper inner goals that lead them, and every sentence they say sounds something a child would say. And this is the biggest flaw of The Chosen one, since the game already offers so little.I cannot recommend The Chosen even by the extremely cheap price it’s selling almost every week, since it feels like content-poor, incomplete and a lazily made product that barely got the care it needed. With absolute power comes absolute responsibility, and just because you have a powerful game engine you can use, doesn’t mean you should create a sub-par game you wouldn’t want to play and charge people money for it. I only hope that developers will grow mature soon and respect the power of making games more."
