76561198169832138,Recommended,434420,32575784,Posted: 19 June,all,jwmmail,"If you are considering this title accept that it is only one part (the bigger part) of a two part project. When you buy ""Chosen"" you will want to buy ""Chosen 2"" at the same time. Together these two games form a single narrative. This narrative is a short (less than 10 hours) simple Ameri-JRPG. It doesn't do anything fancy and it doesn't try to.It is my suspicion that this game was a passion project and a training exercise for the developer. Part 1 ""feels"" a bit under polished. The combat is a little too easy. The protagonist travels with three female companions all of whom choose to travel in lingerie. This feels very amateurish, but also in its way feels very Japanese. The author consistently uses, ""your"" when they should be using ""you're"" … it's little things that make this game feel like a fledgling project.Part 2 takes noteworthy strides forward. The companion characters wear real clothes. The interface gets some polish. The combat is more balanced. It was early in Part 2 that I experienced my first total party death and game over screen. I suddenly became aware that I was going to have to pay more attention. The game isn't overly difficult, or even difficult. It just wasn't a ""cake-walk"" any more. That was better.But combat isn't really what this game (or other similar RPG-Maker games) is about. It's about a love for a dying genre of JRPG, and the stories that only these games can tell. It's the reason the we buy games like this. And, as yet another entry in the slog of RPG-Maker amateurware, Chosen doesn't do anything new. But, it doesn't do anything particularly wrong either. The story is well paced and sometimes interesting. You won't spend too much time trying to figure out where you need to go, or what you need to do. Everything is intuitive and the experience is smooth.I am going to keep my eyes on this developer because they have good instincts for this kind of game and how it should play. Because the best thing about Chosen and Chosen 2 is that I enjoyed playing them. These games are fun, and at the end of the day, isn't that what matters most?"
